The takeaway

Search your codebase for finally { blocks. The ones that exist only to release a resource — clear a timeout, remove a listener, close a connection — are candidates for using. Each one can move its cleanup from a finally block to the line where the resource is allocated, making the lifetime visible at a glance and eliminating a whole class of cleanup bugs.

using doesn't replace try/catch for error handling. It replaces the finally that does nothing but clean up. That's a smaller scope, but it's the scope you write wrong the most often.

